<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lundblad" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesovelia horvathi" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horvathi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">Mesovelia horvathi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(s.l.) Lundblad, 1933 (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Lundblad, O." journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Hydrobiologie. Supplement." pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" pagination="1 - 489" refId="B5982027" refString="Lundblad, O., 1933. Zur Kenntnis der aquatilen und semi-aquatilen Hemipteren von Sumatra, Java und Bali. Archiv fuer Hydrobiologie. Supplement. 12: 1 - 489" title="Zur Kenntnis der aquatilen und semi-aquatilen Hemipteren von Sumatra, Java und Bali" volume="12" year="1933">Lundblad 1933</bibRefCitation>
) was reported from Australia, China, India, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Philippines (see Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5979098" captionText="Figure 7. Distribution of the collecting sites of Gerromorpha material (part 1) treated in this study." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e56883.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/467247" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">7</figureCitation>
for new records), Sri Lanka, Singapore, Thailand, and Vietnam (
<bibRefCitation author="Lundblad, O." journalOrPublisher="Entomologisk Tidskrift" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" pagination="1 - 9" refId="B5979392" refString="Lundblad, O., 1937. Einige neue oder wenig bekannte ostasiatische Rhagovelia -Arten. Entomologisk Tidskrift 58: 1 - 9" title="Einige neue oder wenig bekannte ostasiatische Rhagovelia - Arten" volume="58" year="1937">Lundblad 1937</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Chandra, K." journalOrPublisher="Biodiversity Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" pagination="209 - 212" refId="B5978692" refString="Chandra, K., Jehamalar, E. E., 2011. New records of Gerromorpha, Leptopodomorpha and Nepomorpha (Heteroptera, Insecta) from Madhya Pradesh, India. Biodiversity Journal 2: 209 - 212" title="New records of Gerromorpha, Leptopodomorpha and Nepomorpha (Heteroptera, Insecta) from Madhya Pradesh, India" volume="2" year="2011">Chandra and Jehamalar 2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Yang, C. M." journalOrPublisher="The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" pagination="53 - 60" refId="B5979633" refString="Yang, C. M., Murphy, D., 2011. Guide to the Aquatic Heteroptera of Singapore and Peninsular Malaysia. 6. Mesoveliidae, with description of a new species from Singapore. The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology 59 (1): 53 - 60" title="Guide to the Aquatic Heteroptera of Singapore and Peninsular Malaysia. 6. Mesoveliidae, with description of a new species from Singapore" volume="59" year="2011">Yang and Murphy 2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Zettel, H." journalOrPublisher="Zeitschrift der Arbeitsgemeinschaft Oesterreichischer Entomologen" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" pagination="85 - 140" refId="B5979710" refString="Zettel, H., 2014. Annotated catalogue of semi-aquatic bugs (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Gerromorpha) of Luzon Island, the Philippines, with descriptions of new species. Zeitschrift der Arbeitsgemeinschaft Oesterreichischer Entomologen 66: 85 - 140" title="Annotated catalogue of semi-aquatic bugs (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Gerromorpha) of Luzon Island, the Philippines, with descriptions of new species" volume="66" year="2014">Zettel 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">
For identification, refer to the key by 
<bibRefCitation author="Yang, C. M." journalOrPublisher="The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" pagination="53 - 60" refId="B5979633" refString="Yang, C. M., Murphy, D., 2011. Guide to the Aquatic Heteroptera of Singapore and Peninsular Malaysia. 6. Mesoveliidae, with description of a new species from Singapore. The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology 59 (1): 53 - 60" title="Guide to the Aquatic Heteroptera of Singapore and Peninsular Malaysia. 6. Mesoveliidae, with description of a new species from Singapore" volume="59" year="2011">Yang and Murphy (2011)</bibRefCitation>
. More recently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Jehamalar, E. E." journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" pagination="471 - 496" refId="B5979254" refString="Jehamalar, E. E., Chandra, K., Polhemus, D., 2019. Review of the Mesovelia horvathi species complex (Hemiptera: Gerromorpha: Mesoveliidae), with the description of seven new species from India. Zootaxa 4651 (3): 471 - 496" title="Review of the Mesovelia horvathi species complex (Hemiptera: Gerromorpha: Mesoveliidae), with the description of seven new species from India" volume="4651" year="2019">Jehamalar et al. (2019)</bibRefCitation>
have shown that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lundblad" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesovelia horvathi" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horvathi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">Mesovelia horvathi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
consists of a complex of closely-related species. At least two species of this complex occur in the Philippines. Their correct names remain uncertain. As a result, we refrain from concluding that the previous records from other areas in the Philippines and specimens in this study are indeed 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. horvathi" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" rank="species" species="horvathi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">M. horvathi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">Habitat</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lundblad" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesovelia horvathi" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horvathi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">Mesovelia horvathi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Lundblad, 1933 is common in plains and mountains in stagnant, slow flowing and even in brackish water (
<bibRefCitation author="Yang, C. M." journalOrPublisher="The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" pagination="53 - 60" refId="B5979633" refString="Yang, C. M., Murphy, D., 2011. Guide to the Aquatic Heteroptera of Singapore and Peninsular Malaysia. 6. Mesoveliidae, with description of a new species from Singapore. The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology 59 (1): 53 - 60" title="Guide to the Aquatic Heteroptera of Singapore and Peninsular Malaysia. 6. Mesoveliidae, with description of a new species from Singapore" volume="59" year="2011">Yang and Murphy 2011</bibRefCitation>
). We found the species in similar, partly identical habitats like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Horvath" authorityYear="1895" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesovelia vittigera" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittigera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">Mesovelia vittigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but so far, never syntopic with the former species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
